      "skill_tag": "trig_equations",
      "parts": [
        {
          "label": "a",
          "body": "Solve $2\\cos x = \\sqrt{3}$ for $0 \\le x \\le 2\\pi$.",
          "marks": 4,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "isolate: $\\cos x = \\tfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$x = \\dfrac{\\pi}{6}$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "use the symmetry of cosine: $x = 2\\pi - \\tfrac{\\pi}{6}$"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$x = \\dfrac{11\\pi}{6}$"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$x = \\dfrac{\\pi}{6}$ and $x = \\dfrac{11\\pi}{6}$",
          "solution": "**Plan:** isolate the cosine, then use the unit circle.$$\\cos x = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\Rightarrow x = \\frac{\\pi}{6} \\text{ or } x = 2\\pi - \\frac{\\pi}{6} = \\frac{11\\pi}{6}$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(simplify(2*cos(pi/6) - sqrt(3)), 0)",
            "Eq(simplify(2*cos(11*pi/6) - sqrt(3)), 0)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "label": "b",
          "body": "Hence state the number of solutions of $2\\cos x = \\sqrt{3}$ for $0 \\le x \\le 4\\pi$.",
          "marks": 2,
          "markscheme": [
            {
              "mark": "M1",
              "note": "cosine has period $2\\pi$, so each period contributes two solutions"
            },
            {
              "mark": "A1",
              "note": "$4$ solutions"
            }
          ],
          "answer": "$4$",
          "solution": "Each $2\\pi$-period contains the two solutions found in part (a), and $[0, 4\\pi]$ spans two periods:$$2 \\times 2 = 4 \\text{ solutions.}$$",
          "verify": [
            "Eq(2*2, 4)"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
